Task 2 - BUILD SUPERVISED LEARNING MODELS¶

In this task, we will solve a classification problem that is based on the happiness data we dealt with in the previous task: We have seen the relationship between the subjective happiness and other features of citizens of different countries in the world. In the era of globalization, many people have unprecedented freedom to move across countries. Just like the variety of economical, political, and environmental reasons for people to be happy/unhappy, people decide to leave their home country for other countries for different motives.

We are curious if the same features of a country that were used to predict happiness, and even happiness itself, can be help us predict if a country has a positive or negative net migration, meaning there are more people moving to than leaving the country or the opposite. Specifically, we would inspect the migration status of year 2017, which is the most recent year that World Bank's Net Migration indicator data is available.

This is a typical binary classification problem. We label a country with positive net migration class 1 and a country with negative migration class 0.

Integration¶

We have two data sources: the cleaned.csv we acquired previously, containing features around happiness score across countries, and World Bank Net Migration indicator.

def get_all_country_data_for_years(indicator_code, start_year, end_year, per_page = 5000):
    TEMPLATE = "https://api.worldbank.org/v2/country/all/indicator/%s?format=json&date=%s:%s&per_page=%s"
    URL = TEMPLATE % (indicator_code, start_year, end_year, per_page)
    result = json.loads(requests.get(URL).content)
    if result[0]["per_page"] < result[0]["total"]:
        URL = TEMPLATE % (indicator_code, start_year,
                          end_year, result[0]["total"])
        result = json.loads(requests.get(URL).content)
    return result
start_year, end_year = min(data["year"]), max(data["year"])

Building classifiers¶

We will build several classifiers using different algorithms: KNN, Decision Tree, and Naive Bayes. Then we can compare the three models and choose the best one based on the cross-validation scores.

KNN

KNN, among the three algorithms, involves the idea of distance and therefore we need to scale the data first:

TASK 3 – BUILD UNSUPERVISED LEARNING MODELS¶

Feature selection for unsupervised learning is beyond the scope of this course. One of the method is called Principle Feature Analysis. The code below is a implementation of PFA from here.

In [588]:
class PFA(object):
    def __init__(self, n_features, q=None):
        self.q = q
        self.n_features = n_features

    def fit(self, X):
        if not self.q:
            self.q = X.shape[1]

        sc = StandardScaler()
        X = sc.fit_transform(X)

        pca = PCA(n_components=self.q).fit(X)
        A_q = pca.components_.T

        kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=self.n_features).fit(A_q)
        clusters = kmeans.predict(A_q)
        cluster_centers = kmeans.cluster_centers_

        dists = defaultdict(list)
        for i, c in enumerate(clusters):
            dist = euclidean_distances([A_q[i, :]], [cluster_centers[c, :]])[0][0]
            dists[c].append((i, dist))

        self.indices_ = [sorted(f, key=lambda x: x[1])[0][0] for f in dists.values()]
        self.features_ = X[:, self.indices_]

We use PFA to reduce our features to 3: log GDP per capita, social support, and freedom to make life choice.

Task 4¶

Introduction¶

In this assignment, we have done some further investigation on the WHR data. In particular, we have focused on:

  • Build a model that predict if a country has positive or negative migration
  • Build a model that divide data into some clusters and see if there's some interesting fact revealed

The data sources we use are the cleaned WHR data from previous assignment, as well as the Net Migration indicator data from World Bank.

Process¶

To build the model to predict net migration, we first need some labeled data, as this is a supervised learning problem. Such data is fetched from World Bank API and integrated into our WHR data in a similar manner to the previous assignment (handling country name variant, etc.)

Then we explore what features may be useful in predicting the migration class, and use these features as candidate to algorithmically select best features from. From here on, we tried the combination of features and different classification algorithms: KNN, decision tree, and naive Bayes. For KNN, we also try to find the optimal number of neighbors, and for decision tree, we also try to find the optimal tree depth.

After comparing all kinds of combinations, we eventually pick decision tree with max depth 5 as our classifier to predict if a country has positive or negative migration. Our classifier outperforms by much the base line dummy classifier.

Next we use KMeans algorithm to divide our data into clusters. We use PFA to pick three principle features (log GDP per capita, social support, freedom) and then build the model based on them. After comparing the WSS against K, we pick k = 3 for the result model.

Conclusion¶

To predict if a country has positive or negative migration, we use the following features: Log GDP per capita, social support, expected health life, freedom to make life choice, perception of corruption, democratic quality , service deliver quality, Gini from 2010 to 2017, urban population percentage, trust Score by WVS, and subjective happiness score, to build a decision tree model with max depth 5. The model has reached roughly 0.72 F1 score in cross-validation.

For clustering, we have used log GDP per capita, social support, freedom to build a KMeans model, with K = 3. The result clusters are intertwined and probably not very meaningful, but we can still observe some interesting facts from it. Specifically, we observe that the data of developed countries are distributed in higher density, implying they have a similar performance in each aspect.
